WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.960
the Director of Life Sciences and Healthcare here at Posit.

00:00:03.960 --> 00:00:05.680
Very excited to bring to you today

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:09.340
the ninth installment of our Life Sciences Series.

00:00:09.340 --> 00:00:11.920
Previously, we have highlighted Roche, BMS,

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:15.820
Merck, GSK, Novartis, Johnson & Johnson, and others.

00:00:15.820 --> 00:00:18.920
And you can find these Posit webinars linked below.

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:20.480
And today we have an exciting webinar

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:23.040
featuring the work of Novo Nordisk.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.760
We're going to highlight the journey

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:27.559
to an R based FDA submission.

00:00:27.559 --> 00:00:29.799
And we'll kick off the presentation today

00:00:29.799 --> 00:00:33.000
with Ari, the Principal Statistical Programmer.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.919
We'll then pass it over to Stephan, Statistician.

00:00:35.919 --> 00:00:39.439
And then we'll end with Anders, Statistical Specialist.

00:00:39.439 --> 00:00:42.279
It's such an exciting time for open source drug development.

00:00:42.279 --> 00:00:45.560
From 2017 to 2020,

00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:48.000
we had important things that had happened.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.360
R and Pharma, the R validation hub, the Pharmaverse.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:53.660
And then into 2021,

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:56.759
we had an R pilot submission to the FDA.

00:00:56.759 --> 00:00:59.000
And now a little over a year later,

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.160
we have a full submission in R by Novo.

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:06.239
And it's so exciting to see the pharmas are migrating

00:01:06.239 --> 00:01:09.599
to an open source backbone for their clinical reporting.

00:01:09.599 --> 00:01:12.800
And what sets Novo apart is the depth

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:15.120
for which they're tackling this effort.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:17.360
The change management from a multilingual

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:19.080
statistical computing environment

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:21.800
to the package management and validation

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:24.519
and to the end user support and education.

00:01:24.519 --> 00:01:28.559
For example, they even have their own internal R podcast.

00:01:28.559 --> 00:01:31.400
And all the while contributing to community efforts

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:34.320
like R and Pharma, the Pharmaverse, the pilot submissions.

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:38.760
And so it's with great joy to bring you this session today.

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:41.320
And now I will pass it over to Ari.

00:01:43.639 --> 00:01:44.720
Thank you, Phil.

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:46.680
We're so excited to be here

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:49.239
and to be able to tell our story

00:01:49.239 --> 00:01:51.160
of all the ups and downs we've experienced

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:52.940
in the past few years.

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:56.639
Before we begin, I just have to say that

00:01:57.639 --> 00:02:01.120
this presentation represents the view of the office

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:02.800
and not necessarily New Orleans.

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:06.199
And any of the regulatory communication that we'll show here

00:02:06.199 --> 00:02:08.520
will not be applicable to all projects.

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:10.839
So please communicate with the appropriate

00:02:10.839 --> 00:02:13.119
health authorities about your submission.

00:02:14.720 --> 00:02:17.839
Without further ado then, earlier this year,

00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:22.240
we submitted our first R-based submission to FDA,

00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:26.039
PMDA and other health authorities around the world.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:28.800
And this happened early in 2023.

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:31.759
And we have multiple learnings and feedback

00:02:31.759 --> 00:02:34.240
from authorities that we will share later on

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:35.639
in the presentation as well.

00:02:36.559 --> 00:02:39.080
Incidentally, this year Novo Nordisk

00:02:39.080 --> 00:02:43.240
is actually celebrating its 100th anniversary.

00:02:44.279 --> 00:02:47.399
And Novo Nordisk started in 1923

00:02:47.399 --> 00:02:50.399
as Nordic Insulin Laboratory.

00:02:50.399 --> 00:02:53.199
And it was at a later merger with Novo Industry

00:02:53.199 --> 00:02:55.440
that the current name Novo Nordisk was formed.

00:02:56.360 --> 00:02:58.720
Here in Novo Nordisk, we focused on treatments

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:01.600
for people living with serious chronic diseases.

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:04.199
And we have a strong history in diabetes

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:08.440
and now in obesity for which you may know the company for.

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:13.800
In biostatistics where we three sit,

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:16.839
we work with the first three steps shown here.

00:03:16.839 --> 00:03:19.320
So we work with the clinical trials,

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:22.820
data and evidence generation and approval activities.

00:03:23.919 --> 00:03:26.919
In the evidence that we submit to authorities,

00:03:26.919 --> 00:03:29.679
we include STDM and Adam datasets

00:03:29.679 --> 00:03:33.720
that follow industry standards such as the CDISC.

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:37.440
We submit programs, documentation, analysis,

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:40.600
tables, figures, listings, you name it.

00:03:40.600 --> 00:03:42.160
And what we're going to share today

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:46.000
is our story of getting to do all of this with R.

00:03:48.279 --> 00:03:50.240
Now going back to the beginning,

00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:54.360
then there's one thing we really, really want to highlight

00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:56.399
and one thing that permeates everything

00:03:56.399 --> 00:03:58.199
in this presentation.

00:03:58.199 --> 00:04:00.479
And we put this quote on the slide,

00:04:00.479 --> 00:04:02.440
that the goal is the transformation process

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:04.839
that is revolutionary in result,

00:04:04.839 --> 00:04:07.039
but evolutionary in execution.

00:04:08.759 --> 00:04:11.639
Or in other words, it's more a matter of taking steps

00:04:11.639 --> 00:04:15.240
rather than thinking about how big those steps should be.

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:18.720
Now, back in 2015, we had a lot of people

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:23.720
Now back in 2015, we all joined the biostatistics

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:27.160
in Novo to an environment where everything was dominated

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:29.000
by the SAS programming language.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:33.000
We loved R and we quickly noticed

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.799
a huge R shaped hole at Novo.

00:04:36.799 --> 00:04:38.200
And to our surprise,

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:41.559
Gibbs and version control systems were also absent

00:04:41.559 --> 00:04:44.559
and we were not the first to notice this here.

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:48.519
So we got R installed on our local computers

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:50.440
and we used it every now and then

00:04:50.440 --> 00:04:53.559
for these one-off non-critical tasks.

00:04:56.799 --> 00:05:01.799
In 2017, 2016, we started to introduce R to management

00:05:02.239 --> 00:05:04.440
and our stakeholders and colleagues

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:07.000
for non-GXP related work,

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.160
where we were showcasing Shiny

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:11.640
as an incredible powerful framework

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:14.880
for data visualization

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:16.959
that you just couldn't get anywhere else.

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:20.679
We had a Shiny app for data exploration,

00:05:20.679 --> 00:05:22.000
the bottom one you see here,

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.480
and one for assistance in pharmacokinetic

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:27.640
and pharmacodynamic data reviews.

00:05:28.559 --> 00:05:32.160
We were also using R for crawling SAS logs,

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:34.559
comparing stuff and checking stuff.

00:05:35.679 --> 00:05:38.559
And development of this continued through 2017.

00:05:38.559 --> 00:05:42.679
And in 2018, we continued to push

00:05:42.679 --> 00:05:46.320
for adopting some use of R.

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:48.760
And the collection of R programs we were using

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:51.440
had grown so much that we now combined it

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:55.200
into a single package named NNR.

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:57.279
And this package was the first thing

00:05:57.279 --> 00:05:59.079
we put in version control

00:05:59.079 --> 00:06:02.200
and we also set up pipelines for testing it.

00:06:04.279 --> 00:06:09.200
Now, come 2019, where we finally saw a commitment

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:14.040
from above to report a trial in another language than SAS.

00:06:14.079 --> 00:06:17.279
I remember receiving this strategy email

00:06:17.279 --> 00:06:20.519
and Stephan was sitting at the desk right next to mine.

00:06:20.519 --> 00:06:21.640
And I showed him this

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:25.119
and we literally ran into our manager and said,

00:06:25.119 --> 00:06:28.679
if anybody's going to do this, it has to be us.

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:31.040
And it wouldn't take long

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:33.359
until we got the nod to go ahead for this.

00:06:33.359 --> 00:06:37.720
And we both thought, shit, it's real.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:41.519
How do we even do this?

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:44.119
We don't have a TXP environment for R.

00:06:44.119 --> 00:06:46.040
We don't have a system for packages.

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:49.480
I mean, we don't even have a strategy for packages.

00:06:50.799 --> 00:06:52.200
So we get down to this

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:54.959
and I'll hand it over to Stephan to tell you more.

00:06:55.959 --> 00:06:57.040
Yes.

00:06:57.040 --> 00:06:59.079
So at this point,

00:06:59.079 --> 00:07:02.320
we are still using R from all local laptops

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:05.760
without any system basically at all.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:07.000
So we were in dire need

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.000
of a statistical computing environment.

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:13.200
And actually our initial thoughts

00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:16.600
regarding this new environment were in terms of stakeholders

00:07:18.399 --> 00:07:21.119
and the change management of those.

00:07:21.119 --> 00:07:24.200
So we wanted to produce table figures and listings

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:25.839
that were identical to those

00:07:25.839 --> 00:07:27.760
that were already produced in SAS.

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:30.519
Because this mean that there would be no change

00:07:30.519 --> 00:07:33.119
for the stakeholders regarding the language

00:07:33.119 --> 00:07:34.559
that we would choose.

00:07:34.559 --> 00:07:38.079
It would also mean that we could use the existing workflows

00:07:38.079 --> 00:07:40.119
that we had set up for producing reports

00:07:40.119 --> 00:07:43.119
that we're going to send to authorities.

00:07:43.119 --> 00:07:48.119
And we could on the same trial work on both R and SAS.

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:54.200
We also wanted a system that were hassle-free

00:07:54.200 --> 00:07:55.160
for the end user.

00:07:56.239 --> 00:07:59.679
So we were trying to cater to our colleagues

00:07:59.679 --> 00:08:02.000
that were used to programming SAS.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.600
So we really wanted a server

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:07.040
that they didn't need to think so much about packages,

00:08:07.079 --> 00:08:09.480
environment as such,

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:12.760
but more about getting to the actual programming.

00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:14.559
So it should also be so that

00:08:14.559 --> 00:08:17.040
if you've got a code snippet from your colleague,

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:17.880
you should be pretty sure

00:08:17.880 --> 00:08:21.559
that that would also work on your computer,

00:08:21.559 --> 00:08:25.000
given that you were using the same version of R.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:28.559
And then finally, with this new SCE,

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:31.359
we really wanted to highlight version control.

00:08:31.359 --> 00:08:32.640
So remember at this time,

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:36.239
we weren't using a version control basically at all.

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:39.520
We had a few things that we had it on,

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:42.599
but not for anything regarding trials.

00:08:42.599 --> 00:08:45.239
So here we wanted to produce an easy way

00:08:45.239 --> 00:08:48.719
for initiating a version control for both trial

00:08:48.719 --> 00:08:51.919
and collaboration work, such as packages.

00:08:54.479 --> 00:08:58.760
We quickly saw that these four things

00:08:58.760 --> 00:09:01.599
would be the pillars of our infrastructure.

00:09:01.599 --> 00:09:06.599
We really wanted an IDE based on RStudio workflow

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:09.719
or the opposite, Workbench,

00:09:09.719 --> 00:09:11.840
because it was such a great IDE

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:15.039
and familiar to so many R users.

00:09:15.039 --> 00:09:17.799
We did, however, want to make it the server-based solution

00:09:17.799 --> 00:09:20.000
so that you would simply log in to the server

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.559
and be sure that you were in common ground

00:09:21.559 --> 00:09:23.200
with everybody else.

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:25.760
Then we wanted to use Git for our version control

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:29.880
because that was so familiar with most of the R programmers

00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:31.359
as we had used it in the past.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:35.320
And it will also come with great features,

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:37.919
such as feature branching for our development stuff.

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:41.359
We wanted to use Azure DevOps,

00:09:41.359 --> 00:09:44.719
both for project management, so for organizing tasks,

00:09:44.719 --> 00:09:48.239
but also for all of the code repositories

00:09:49.200 --> 00:09:50.640
that we could share those.

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:53.119
And of course, for CICD pipelines.

00:09:54.599 --> 00:09:57.000
And finally, but definitely not least,

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.280
we wanted to use deposit package manager

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:03.200
for all things regarding R packages.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:07.119
We wanted to use it to share our internal packages.

00:10:07.119 --> 00:10:10.799
And we also wanted to use it for creating subset of packages

00:10:10.799 --> 00:10:13.640
that we will call approved packages for use.

00:10:15.799 --> 00:10:18.039
Now, when we started working on this SCE,

00:10:18.039 --> 00:10:19.760
we were hit pretty hard

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:22.239
by the number of things you need to consider

00:10:22.239 --> 00:10:24.599
for making a GXP compliant system.

00:10:24.599 --> 00:10:26.640
I won't go through all of these now,

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:29.640
but suffice it to say that there is a lot to think about.

00:10:30.039 --> 00:10:34.039
And so instead of starting from scratch,

00:10:34.039 --> 00:10:37.039
we took a look at what do we already have.

00:10:37.039 --> 00:10:39.960
I mean, at the time we were able to produce

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:42.080
all of the stuff that we needed

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:45.200
for the reports that were going to the authorities.

00:10:46.280 --> 00:10:47.880
So instead of starting from scratch,

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:50.400
we wanted to piggyback on what we already had.

00:10:51.719 --> 00:10:54.000
So we wanted to launch a computer

00:10:55.200 --> 00:10:57.200
next to the one we already had.

00:10:57.200 --> 00:10:58.359
Now, the one we already had

00:10:58.359 --> 00:11:01.119
were located somewhere in Copenhagen,

00:11:01.119 --> 00:11:05.679
having a file share with all of the data and output and such.

00:11:05.679 --> 00:11:07.919
So we wanted to put it next to it,

00:11:07.919 --> 00:11:10.239
except we didn't really want to put it next to it.

00:11:10.239 --> 00:11:12.159
We wanted to put it in the cloud

00:11:13.559 --> 00:11:15.000
because we had no idea

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.080
how many users were going to be on the system.

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:18.960
There'll probably be a few in the beginning

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:21.840
and then a lot as time progressed.

00:11:22.719 --> 00:11:25.960
And luckily we got a really, really good cloud architect

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:27.440
to help us out on this.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
And together we quickly saw

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.640
that in order to fill all of these GXP requirements,

00:11:35.640 --> 00:11:38.479
we needed full infrastructure as code.

00:11:38.479 --> 00:11:41.320
And we needed to have version control on that code

00:11:41.320 --> 00:11:43.840
so that we could see who changed what and when.

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:48.200
We also, while I quickly identified

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:50.599
the need of machine images.

00:11:50.599 --> 00:11:53.239
So for all of our compute instances,

00:11:53.239 --> 00:11:54.919
they should be built on a machine image

00:11:54.919 --> 00:11:56.479
so that we could spin it up

00:11:56.479 --> 00:11:58.599
and be sure we would get the same result

00:11:58.599 --> 00:12:00.960
the next time as we did before.

00:12:01.799 --> 00:12:06.479
And finally, as we didn't want to do in a manual task,

00:12:06.479 --> 00:12:09.880
we wanted to use release pipelines

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:12.200
for releasing the entire infrastructure

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:13.799
in different environments.

00:12:17.239 --> 00:12:21.239
So in 2020, we released our first GXP

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:26.440
and classified environment for doing R stuff.

00:12:28.200 --> 00:12:29.799
It would look something like this

00:12:29.799 --> 00:12:33.239
where a user would come in from the workbench.

00:12:33.239 --> 00:12:36.440
Here they would have access to the RStudio IDE.

00:12:36.440 --> 00:12:37.599
They could program in R

00:12:37.599 --> 00:12:39.719
and they would have access to all of the packages

00:12:39.719 --> 00:12:42.719
they would need from the Posit package manager.

00:12:43.719 --> 00:12:46.640
They could see all of their repositories

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:48.919
and get those from the Azure DevOps.

00:12:49.799 --> 00:12:53.599
And they could install their code on a home directory,

00:12:53.599 --> 00:12:56.000
which was a file share in the cloud.

00:12:57.280 --> 00:13:00.239
Now we still had all of our data residing

00:13:00.239 --> 00:13:03.159
on our old computer on the file share,

00:13:03.159 --> 00:13:05.280
which were located somewhere in Copenhagen.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:08.840
In terms of features,

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:11.400
we didn't do much the first couple of years,

00:13:11.400 --> 00:13:14.239
but we did make a larger machines.

00:13:14.239 --> 00:13:16.599
Then we make more workbench machines

00:13:16.599 --> 00:13:18.280
and a load balancer in front.

00:13:18.719 --> 00:13:21.400
Because of the growing need for computation

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:22.599
in regards to the users.

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:25.640
And then come 2022,

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:28.719
and we finally started to introduce new features.

00:13:28.719 --> 00:13:32.280
We introduced Python on the workbench server

00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:35.880
and PyPy on the Posit package manager.

00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:37.960
We introduced new IDEs,

00:13:37.960 --> 00:13:41.479
so that the programmer would be able to select the IDE

00:13:41.479 --> 00:13:43.320
he or she was most comfortable with.

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:45.919
And we also introduced a lot of new features

00:13:45.919 --> 00:13:48.359
that the IDE he or she was most comfortable with.

00:13:49.919 --> 00:13:53.039
Then we introduced a caching system.

00:13:53.039 --> 00:13:57.159
And this was because the file share located in Copenhagen

00:13:57.159 --> 00:14:01.440
had an insanely slow connection to the cloud.

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:03.799
So this way we would only have to wait

00:14:03.799 --> 00:14:06.159
for a dataset to be transferred once,

00:14:06.159 --> 00:14:09.119
and then everybody else could use the data from the cache.

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:14.760
We also released a Posit Connect instance.

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:18.840
Mostly for sharing our markdown documents

00:14:18.840 --> 00:14:21.280
and running Shiny applications.

00:14:21.280 --> 00:14:24.000
Now this was built on the same image

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:25.520
as the workbench machine,

00:14:25.520 --> 00:14:28.039
which meant that if it worked on the workbench machine,

00:14:28.039 --> 00:14:31.640
it would almost certainly also work on the Connect instance.

00:14:33.479 --> 00:14:37.239
But we did have one problem that was still remaining here.

00:14:37.239 --> 00:14:39.080
And that were some users,

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:41.119
regardless of how big we tried to make

00:14:41.119 --> 00:14:43.159
these workbench machine,

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:46.200
would hog up all of the resources that were available.

00:14:47.239 --> 00:14:50.679
So in 2023, we finally released

00:14:50.679 --> 00:14:52.080
a high performance compute cluster

00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:54.919
in the type of a Kubernetes cluster,

00:14:54.919 --> 00:14:58.640
where a user could spin up a Docker image.

00:15:00.599 --> 00:15:04.599
And through that, they would get the entire IDE,

00:15:04.599 --> 00:15:05.960
but they would be ensured

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:09.719
that they would not step on the toes of anybody else,

00:15:10.719 --> 00:15:11.840
any of the other users.

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:13.760
And speaking of users,

00:15:13.760 --> 00:15:17.799
let's just take a look at the user uptake on this system.

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:21.719
So here we have depicted the number of users

00:15:21.719 --> 00:15:23.479
that we have on the Y-axis

00:15:23.479 --> 00:15:25.520
and the timeline on the X-axis.

00:15:27.039 --> 00:15:28.760
And we can see that we didn't have that many users

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:31.159
in the beginning as we expected.

00:15:31.159 --> 00:15:32.880
These users were mainly those

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:35.119
that were assigned to the trials

00:15:35.119 --> 00:15:37.320
that were going to produce results

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:39.799
that were going to use R for that.

00:15:40.640 --> 00:15:42.440
But as you can see, the time grows,

00:15:42.440 --> 00:15:45.400
we can see many, many, many more users.

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:46.239
And in the end,

00:15:46.239 --> 00:15:47.559
we're actually not only supporting

00:15:47.559 --> 00:15:49.760
the biostatistics department,

00:15:49.760 --> 00:15:53.599
but also users from other departments within Nominoidisk.

00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:57.440
And I thought we would have had such a great success

00:15:57.440 --> 00:15:59.719
in the user uptake on the system,

00:15:59.719 --> 00:16:01.799
if we didn't have a really great strategy

00:16:01.799 --> 00:16:03.679
on handling packages.

00:16:03.679 --> 00:16:05.880
And now, Anders will take us through

00:16:05.880 --> 00:16:09.280
the handling of these packages from CRAN.

00:16:09.320 --> 00:16:10.239
Yeah.

00:16:10.239 --> 00:16:12.280
Thank you for that, Stephan.

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:16.440
So the NN package management really started in 2020

00:16:16.440 --> 00:16:17.280
with the...

00:16:19.159 --> 00:16:20.000
Sorry.

00:16:21.880 --> 00:16:26.880
Remember that our organization was used to SAS and SAS only.

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:28.719
So introducing a new language

00:16:28.719 --> 00:16:31.520
that is very much unlike SAS, that's challenging.

00:16:31.520 --> 00:16:33.640
So SAS is nice and simple.

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:36.440
You need to install SAS 9.4.

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:37.479
It's 10 years old.

00:16:37.479 --> 00:16:39.599
It has been patched a couple of times,

00:16:39.599 --> 00:16:40.880
but it's still in use.

00:16:40.880 --> 00:16:43.960
R on the other hand, that's not as simple.

00:16:43.960 --> 00:16:46.559
R is evolving at a higher pace.

00:16:46.559 --> 00:16:49.719
And R also has all of these packages.

00:16:49.719 --> 00:16:51.239
And each of these packages,

00:16:51.239 --> 00:16:53.000
they come with their own versions,

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:54.239
they come at different times,

00:16:54.239 --> 00:16:55.479
they have their own life.

00:16:56.919 --> 00:16:59.760
So these packages are what makes R great and powerful,

00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:01.280
but there is no free lunch.

00:17:05.119 --> 00:17:06.920
So dependencies between packages,

00:17:07.319 --> 00:17:08.880
they quickly become too complex

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:11.880
if you just pick and choose your versions arbitrarily.

00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:14.400
You need, you'll quickly create a set of packages

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:17.199
that does not work as intended together.

00:17:17.199 --> 00:17:19.160
So we wanted to create an environment

00:17:19.160 --> 00:17:22.239
that is sufficiently fixed and stable,

00:17:22.239 --> 00:17:23.400
but still flexible.

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:25.640
And we opted for this shared baseline model

00:17:25.640 --> 00:17:28.760
as it has now become known.

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:30.839
So here you lock each version of R

00:17:30.839 --> 00:17:33.280
to a particular date and time,

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:35.079
and you install packages in versions

00:17:35.079 --> 00:17:37.760
that were available at that given date.

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:39.359
So we do this so that we know

00:17:39.359 --> 00:17:42.359
that any pair of dependent packages,

00:17:42.359 --> 00:17:44.479
they were tested at that point in time,

00:17:44.479 --> 00:17:47.520
and they were tested that they work together.

00:17:47.520 --> 00:17:48.959
So that means that, for example,

00:17:48.959 --> 00:17:51.079
our R version 4.02,

00:17:51.079 --> 00:17:54.719
that's locked to some date in September, 2020,

00:17:54.719 --> 00:17:58.079
that we will always get dplyr 1.0.2,

00:17:58.079 --> 00:18:02.839
despite how many releases of dplyr that has been since.

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:06.239
So teams simply just choose their version of R.

00:18:06.239 --> 00:18:08.719
They can deviate from the standard ones

00:18:08.719 --> 00:18:10.400
that we have in the system,

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:13.560
but if they do so, they must use renv.

00:18:13.560 --> 00:18:16.560
In general, we actually recommend that you always use renv.

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:21.520
So what packages can and should we use?

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:25.319
Well, they can be roughly categorized in this way.

00:18:25.319 --> 00:18:28.160
So they are the base and recommended packages.

00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:30.239
Those are the ones that ship with R.

00:18:30.239 --> 00:18:34.000
They are low risk, and they are very widely used.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:35.520
The contributed ones are the one

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:37.959
we need to do a risk assessment on.

00:18:37.959 --> 00:18:40.880
So of these, there are the widely used ones.

00:18:40.880 --> 00:18:45.880
They are low risk by virtue of the enormous user base.

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:50.199
There is the well-tested and documented ones.

00:18:50.199 --> 00:18:52.599
They may be more niche,

00:18:52.599 --> 00:18:54.359
but they are still considered low risk.

00:18:54.359 --> 00:18:56.239
It is the risk that pose a problem.

00:18:57.760 --> 00:18:59.599
So when we do a risk assessment,

00:18:59.599 --> 00:19:02.319
we lean heavily on the R Validation Hub's

00:19:02.319 --> 00:19:05.000
recommendations on how to categorize.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:08.520
So the main points of categorization is the type of use,

00:19:08.520 --> 00:19:12.000
the maintenance, the popularity, and so on.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:13.239
So at the end of the day,

00:19:13.239 --> 00:19:15.760
this is just a human risk assessment,

00:19:15.760 --> 00:19:19.400
and the way we prompt this assessment to get made

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:21.119
is by a Shiny app.

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:26.359
So our users can, in the IDE via an add-in,

00:19:26.359 --> 00:19:30.800
they will be able to select a requester app,

00:19:31.800 --> 00:19:33.239
and that simply starts up.

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:36.959
So in the app, they can write what package they desire

00:19:36.959 --> 00:19:38.599
and the reason for it,

00:19:38.599 --> 00:19:41.599
and they can also see which R version

00:19:41.599 --> 00:19:44.719
and version of the package this will be available in.

00:19:46.800 --> 00:19:48.560
So when they submit this request,

00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:53.560
it gets version controlled in Git and gets shipped.

00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:57.640
That kicks off a pipeline and then risk metrics.

00:19:57.640 --> 00:20:02.599
The risk metric page tests or performs risk metrics

00:20:02.599 --> 00:20:05.319
for the package in each version of R that we have

00:20:05.319 --> 00:20:08.160
and that associated library,

00:20:08.160 --> 00:20:12.160
and in all of the environments that we have on the system.

00:20:13.880 --> 00:20:17.000
Manual, sorry, a reviewer can then manually

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:21.520
inspect these results and arrive at an informed decision.

00:20:21.520 --> 00:20:24.439
If the reviewer chooses to approve this,

00:20:24.439 --> 00:20:27.520
then it will get fed to our system code

00:20:27.520 --> 00:20:30.599
and then released upon the next release of that system.

00:20:33.359 --> 00:20:36.520
So we now have a GXP environment

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:39.119
and we have a strategy for packages,

00:20:39.119 --> 00:20:41.119
but we still do not have R code

00:20:41.119 --> 00:20:43.479
for producing tables, figures, and listings.

00:20:43.479 --> 00:20:46.520
We do not have batch execution and logging capabilities

00:20:46.520 --> 00:20:48.760
in R, what about those?

00:20:49.680 --> 00:20:51.880
This is also handled by the packages,

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:54.520
our internal packages,

00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:55.800
and these internal packages,

00:20:55.800 --> 00:20:57.920
they started as a single package,

00:20:57.920 --> 00:21:01.880
one package to rule them all in 2018,

00:21:01.880 --> 00:21:04.199
and this was developed on a local laptop,

00:21:04.199 --> 00:21:05.560
and it was simply a gathering

00:21:05.560 --> 00:21:08.199
of all the usual functions that have been made.

00:21:09.760 --> 00:21:14.640
In 2020, we introduced the nnBiostat package

00:21:14.640 --> 00:21:18.520
that was simply defined as the accepted packages.

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:21.640
So users would write library in nnBiostat

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:23.599
and get the most useful packages.

00:21:26.199 --> 00:21:31.319
In 2021, we realized that nnR had become too big

00:21:31.319 --> 00:21:36.040
and it was split into packages related to specific tasks.

00:21:36.040 --> 00:21:39.319
So nnR then became just a simple umbrella

00:21:39.319 --> 00:21:40.520
of all of these packages,

00:21:40.520 --> 00:21:42.160
like you know from Tidyverse.

00:21:44.839 --> 00:21:47.119
So the most important of our internal packages

00:21:47.119 --> 00:21:48.839
is nnAccess, that is for getting data

00:21:48.839 --> 00:21:51.920
without worrying about paths or data formats.

00:21:51.920 --> 00:21:55.479
It's nnPlot for creating NovoStyle plots.

00:21:55.479 --> 00:21:59.280
It's nnTable, which defines the grammar of tables

00:21:59.280 --> 00:22:03.640
for laying out tables and creating text-based output.

00:22:03.640 --> 00:22:06.719
So we wanted to mimic what we already did in SAS.

00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:10.439
It can also produce HTML outputs.

00:22:10.439 --> 00:22:14.199
We also have nnExport for exporting table figures

00:22:14.199 --> 00:22:18.280
and lists that fit into our production pipeline.

00:22:18.280 --> 00:22:21.239
And we have nnLog for batch execution and logging.

00:22:22.319 --> 00:22:26.359
Here we actually use niraspin to create nice-looking logs.

00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:30.359
So, and although these packages,

00:22:30.359 --> 00:22:32.880
they fit together in a complicated network,

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:35.959
each package is just like in the real world,

00:22:35.959 --> 00:22:37.760
it has its own repo.

00:22:37.760 --> 00:22:41.560
It is managed in an open-source way internally.

00:22:41.560 --> 00:22:44.520
And we have version numbers, a maintainer group,

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:47.040
we have pipelines, and we have boards

00:22:47.040 --> 00:22:50.239
for managing bugs, features, ideas, and much more.

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:56.359
So we aimed to follow a common

00:22:56.359 --> 00:22:59.040
and good software principles of modularity,

00:22:59.040 --> 00:23:03.599
and we tried to build up functionality like Lego bricks.

00:23:03.599 --> 00:23:07.319
So we tried to segregate the responsibility of the packages

00:23:07.319 --> 00:23:10.640
and define appropriate extraction levels.

00:23:10.680 --> 00:23:11.680
So at the bottom here,

00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:14.920
you see the packages that are close to the system.

00:23:14.920 --> 00:23:17.719
They are system-dependent, if you will.

00:23:17.719 --> 00:23:19.479
And on top, you see the packages

00:23:19.479 --> 00:23:21.560
that are close to the task at hand.

00:23:22.719 --> 00:23:24.599
At the top, users shouldn't worry

00:23:24.599 --> 00:23:26.560
about how the data is stored,

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:29.040
where is it stored, and so on.

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:31.319
They should just concentrate on the task.

00:23:32.560 --> 00:23:37.560
So for example, a programmer wishes to use nntfl

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:40.319
to make a mean plot that will call nnAccess

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.599
to fetch ADAM data through a connection set up

00:23:43.599 --> 00:23:45.239
by nnRemote.

00:23:45.239 --> 00:23:46.719
And after the plot has been made,

00:23:46.719 --> 00:23:49.560
nnExport will take care of exporting the data

00:23:49.560 --> 00:23:51.359
to an appropriate data format

00:23:51.359 --> 00:23:53.560
and associated files that we need.

00:23:55.520 --> 00:23:56.959
So this has the benefit

00:23:56.959 --> 00:24:01.359
that we can change underlying architectures in the system

00:24:01.359 --> 00:24:04.920
and simply just do small changes

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:08.040
in the lower-level packages, if you will,

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:10.359
and the users won't see a difference.

00:24:10.359 --> 00:24:11.520
So this is also the reason

00:24:11.520 --> 00:24:16.280
that we could inject a caching system into the system.

00:24:18.079 --> 00:24:22.400
So let's talk about the tool chain that we use in Novo.

00:24:22.400 --> 00:24:25.199
So we use git for version control

00:24:25.199 --> 00:24:30.199
and Azure Pipelines for executing code upon code changes.

00:24:31.439 --> 00:24:35.520
We use useless for the description file and the news file.

00:24:35.520 --> 00:24:39.199
We use package down for generating a website

00:24:40.439 --> 00:24:41.800
of documentation,

00:24:41.800 --> 00:24:44.760
and we use our oxygen to write the documentation.

00:24:46.160 --> 00:24:49.239
We use lifecycle to convey the stability

00:24:49.239 --> 00:24:54.239
or the lifecycle of a function within the packages.

00:24:54.400 --> 00:24:58.079
And we use test.uncover to test the packages.

00:24:58.079 --> 00:24:59.560
We also use our markdown

00:24:59.560 --> 00:25:02.119
for writing longer format documentation

00:25:02.119 --> 00:25:04.040
in the form of vignettes.

00:25:04.040 --> 00:25:08.079
And we use DevTools to do the normal system,

00:25:08.079 --> 00:25:10.359
sorry, the normal package development.

00:25:11.439 --> 00:25:13.079
So upon a code change,

00:25:14.880 --> 00:25:19.319
we will test again the package in a matrix way.

00:25:19.319 --> 00:25:21.560
So we test against all our libraries,

00:25:21.560 --> 00:25:23.079
all our versions of R

00:25:23.079 --> 00:25:28.079
and across all of our system environments.

00:25:29.439 --> 00:25:31.319
So we know that if, for example,

00:25:31.359 --> 00:25:34.319
an upcoming change in development to the system

00:25:34.319 --> 00:25:36.640
will break something in our packages.

00:25:37.599 --> 00:25:40.880
We then build the package and then we release it.

00:25:40.880 --> 00:25:42.280
So in the process of releasing,

00:25:42.280 --> 00:25:45.199
we are updating the package down website

00:25:45.199 --> 00:25:50.199
and we ship it to the internal repo in the package manager.

00:25:50.760 --> 00:25:53.680
So we realized some time ago,

00:25:53.680 --> 00:25:56.239
but we implemented it this year

00:25:56.239 --> 00:26:00.160
that we need the ability to deprecate our versions.

00:26:00.160 --> 00:26:02.839
So say we no longer want to support

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:06.439
the oldest version of R we have and stop,

00:26:06.439 --> 00:26:10.760
then we have made version specific repos

00:26:12.239 --> 00:26:14.160
so we can stop updating that.

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:18.760
This also allows for hotfixes if system changes are needed.

00:26:21.479 --> 00:26:24.719
So we try to ensure a high level of code quality

00:26:24.719 --> 00:26:27.880
by enforcing a main branch policy.

00:26:27.880 --> 00:26:30.520
Nobody can change the main branch directly.

00:26:30.520 --> 00:26:33.079
Only pull requests to the main branch are accepted.

00:26:34.599 --> 00:26:38.800
The pipeline needs to run with success and no errors.

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:42.359
A feature or bot needs to be linked to the pull request

00:26:42.359 --> 00:26:44.920
so we know why we have to change.

00:26:44.920 --> 00:26:48.119
And we need at least one maintainer to approve

00:26:48.119 --> 00:26:50.239
to ensure a code review.

00:26:52.520 --> 00:26:55.040
So now we both have a system

00:26:55.040 --> 00:26:59.640
and we both have the capabilities to execute R code.

00:26:59.640 --> 00:27:01.400
And I think I'll hand it over to Stefan

00:27:01.400 --> 00:27:04.520
so he can show you what it looks like in the real world.

00:27:05.880 --> 00:27:06.719
Yes.

00:27:06.719 --> 00:27:07.560
Thank you.

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:11.719
So I would like to show you how a script usually looks

00:27:11.719 --> 00:27:14.040
when we do it in Noma Nordisk.

00:27:14.040 --> 00:27:15.560
So all programs we have,

00:27:15.560 --> 00:27:18.359
we'll start with the header as I'm showing you now.

00:27:19.640 --> 00:27:22.959
This header will include a short description

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:27.280
of what the program is going to do.

00:27:27.280 --> 00:27:28.119
So in this case,

00:27:28.119 --> 00:27:30.760
we're going to derive summary statistics

00:27:30.760 --> 00:27:35.760
for antibody levels grouped by treatment and gender.

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:39.880
We will have a very small outline

00:27:39.880 --> 00:27:43.160
just indicating the most important steps of the program,

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:45.800
making it easier to read for another programmer.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:50.079
Then the actual code will almost always start

00:27:50.079 --> 00:27:52.959
with a call to library and then biostat.

00:27:52.959 --> 00:27:55.439
This will ensure that we have the packages

00:27:55.439 --> 00:27:58.719
that are most typically used in trial conduct

00:27:58.719 --> 00:28:00.319
loaded into the system

00:28:00.319 --> 00:28:04.000
and that they're loaded in the same order for every program.

00:28:07.079 --> 00:28:10.160
And coming to the main part of the code,

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:13.560
we will almost always use NnAccess

00:28:13.560 --> 00:28:16.640
because that's how we get access to the data.

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:20.319
We can call NnAccess on a specific trial

00:28:20.319 --> 00:28:23.520
that will give us a trial access object.

00:28:24.760 --> 00:28:28.800
A trial access object will have access

00:28:28.800 --> 00:28:31.400
to all of the trial collections

00:28:32.239 --> 00:28:35.000
that are supported for the selected trial.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:39.560
In this case, that could be, for instance, ADAM or SDGM.

00:28:39.560 --> 00:28:43.920
Here we're accessing ADAM data by calling db.adam

00:28:43.920 --> 00:28:48.920
and then we can say what dataset we want to extract.

00:28:49.839 --> 00:28:52.560
And notice here that we do not have any paths here.

00:28:52.560 --> 00:28:56.079
That is taken care of by NnAccess.

00:28:56.079 --> 00:28:59.839
And this means we can actually share this code snippet

00:28:59.839 --> 00:29:02.160
without thinking about where it's actually executed.

00:29:02.160 --> 00:29:04.560
It will always get the same dataset.

00:29:04.560 --> 00:29:08.520
It also allowed us to inject this caching system

00:29:08.520 --> 00:29:13.040
so that every time a user gets a dataset

00:29:13.040 --> 00:29:15.160
that has already been loaded,

00:29:15.160 --> 00:29:19.599
we'll simply use the cache and avoid long waiting time.

00:29:21.560 --> 00:29:23.319
So when having the data,

00:29:23.319 --> 00:29:27.359
we will usually use normal dplyr calculations

00:29:27.359 --> 00:29:30.839
in order to derive the statistics that we want to use.

00:29:30.839 --> 00:29:34.079
So for instance, here, we will filter the data.

00:29:34.079 --> 00:29:37.599
We will summarize the statistics

00:29:37.599 --> 00:29:39.880
that we want to put in the table.

00:29:39.880 --> 00:29:41.400
And then we can, in this case, group them

00:29:41.400 --> 00:29:45.239
by treatment, gender and the parameter code of interest.

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:51.280
This will give us all of the data points

00:29:51.280 --> 00:29:53.959
that we would like to include in our table.

00:29:53.959 --> 00:29:57.520
However, now we had this goal

00:29:58.760 --> 00:30:00.479
that we wanted to produce tables

00:30:01.800 --> 00:30:03.640
that were identical to those produced in SAS

00:30:03.640 --> 00:30:07.640
so that we could be used in our usual pipelines

00:30:07.640 --> 00:30:10.920
for producing reports to authorities.

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:13.680
However, we were using this text-based format

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:18.640
which has the tables that would span multiple pages

00:30:18.640 --> 00:30:20.680
and we had no support for that in R.

00:30:20.680 --> 00:30:24.959
So we created our own package in a table for doing that.

00:30:24.959 --> 00:30:28.160
And here you can initiate a table rather easily.

00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:31.479
You simply state what data is this table going to use

00:30:31.479 --> 00:30:34.000
and then you can say what columns

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:35.959
are going to be in this table.

00:30:35.959 --> 00:30:37.880
You can do some light formatting

00:30:37.880 --> 00:30:40.400
saying that we would like mean and standard deviation

00:30:40.400 --> 00:30:43.520
to be displayed as such,

00:30:43.520 --> 00:30:45.640
or we would like minimum and maximum

00:30:45.640 --> 00:30:48.520
to be displayed with a semicolon between.

00:30:49.520 --> 00:30:52.520
This will produce a table looking like this,

00:30:54.520 --> 00:30:57.040
but we wouldn't be quite happy yet.

00:30:57.040 --> 00:31:00.880
Now, normally we would have all of the summary statistics

00:31:00.880 --> 00:31:02.280
nested under each other.

00:31:03.319 --> 00:31:07.280
So we would have to make the table a bit better,

00:31:07.280 --> 00:31:10.920
but you can note that we have the display

00:31:10.920 --> 00:31:15.280
that we wanted and we said that we wanted in the call.

00:31:17.319 --> 00:31:20.119
In order to nest the summary statistics

00:31:20.119 --> 00:31:21.800
underneath a new variable,

00:31:21.800 --> 00:31:25.479
we use the functionality called addTransLong

00:31:25.479 --> 00:31:29.119
where we can say we want these columns

00:31:29.119 --> 00:31:31.239
nested under a new column called sum.

00:31:32.439 --> 00:31:34.239
And we can also add some formatting, for instance,

00:31:34.239 --> 00:31:37.439
to say how many decimals do we want to apply

00:31:37.439 --> 00:31:39.119
for the different numbers.

00:31:40.359 --> 00:31:42.319
That will produce a table like this,

00:31:42.319 --> 00:31:46.920
which is a bit closer to what we usually have in our reports.

00:31:46.920 --> 00:31:51.760
However, you can see the two new columns down the bottom,

00:31:51.760 --> 00:31:54.640
the sum and the name column.

00:31:54.640 --> 00:31:57.119
Now, we would usually have the sum column

00:31:57.119 --> 00:32:02.119
nested under treatment and perhaps on the gender.

00:32:02.119 --> 00:32:04.439
And the type of summary statistics,

00:32:04.439 --> 00:32:05.839
which is the name column,

00:32:05.839 --> 00:32:09.680
would go under the parameter code.

00:32:09.680 --> 00:32:12.560
So we could use this by having these two

00:32:12.560 --> 00:32:16.040
added lines of code where we have addTransLine

00:32:16.040 --> 00:32:18.239
where we can say summary column

00:32:18.239 --> 00:32:20.119
should be nested under treatment,

00:32:20.119 --> 00:32:23.079
which again should be nested under gender.

00:32:24.319 --> 00:32:26.640
Similar, we can add the stop of the table

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:30.160
saying we want a name nested under the parameter code.

00:32:31.160 --> 00:32:33.280
That will produce a table like this,

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:36.359
which looks like something we've seen before

00:32:36.359 --> 00:32:38.359
that we are going to do in Edna Monodisk.

00:32:40.239 --> 00:32:45.000
We are able to produce other types of tables using this.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.319
So we can export this via FlexTable

00:32:47.319 --> 00:32:49.160
to, for instance, PowerPoint

00:32:49.160 --> 00:32:53.719
or a Word document or directly to HTML.

00:32:55.160 --> 00:32:58.239
But we are focusing today on what do we do

00:32:58.280 --> 00:33:01.160
when we want to export it to a simple file.

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:04.119
And here we use the nnExport functionality

00:33:05.359 --> 00:33:07.760
from the nnExport package.

00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:10.640
Here we can simply say the output name

00:33:12.359 --> 00:33:13.959
that we want to export

00:33:13.959 --> 00:33:16.839
and a file name that we want to export it for.

00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:19.880
Then it will figure out the rest.

00:33:19.880 --> 00:33:22.920
And then we're actually done with a script

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:24.959
that can be used to produce such a table.

00:33:25.959 --> 00:33:27.599
And in order to run it,

00:33:27.599 --> 00:33:30.479
we will use a function called runScript

00:33:30.479 --> 00:33:32.959
that comes from nnLog.

00:33:32.959 --> 00:33:36.680
This function can take both R documents

00:33:36.680 --> 00:33:38.760
and R Markdown documents,

00:33:38.760 --> 00:33:42.119
and it can execute those in batch and in parallel.

00:33:43.239 --> 00:33:45.239
And it will give you some sort of information

00:33:45.239 --> 00:33:48.800
about how the execution actually went.

00:33:48.800 --> 00:33:49.640
In this case,

00:33:49.640 --> 00:33:53.280
we can see that the execution actually had an error.

00:33:53.520 --> 00:33:55.239
So let's inspect that log.

00:33:57.280 --> 00:33:58.319
As you can see here,

00:34:00.079 --> 00:34:02.119
we get a nice HTML log,

00:34:04.400 --> 00:34:07.680
and that log is produced via the spin functionality

00:34:07.680 --> 00:34:09.000
from the NetApp package.

00:34:10.399 --> 00:34:12.840
We can see that we have this header on the top

00:34:13.800 --> 00:34:15.159
that just gives a short description

00:34:15.159 --> 00:34:18.479
of how did the execution actually go.

00:34:18.479 --> 00:34:20.239
Then we have the actual description

00:34:20.239 --> 00:34:23.320
and the outline that we put in top of our document.

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:26.080
And we can see here they are nicely formatted.

00:34:26.080 --> 00:34:28.719
After that comes all of the code chunks that we have.

00:34:29.919 --> 00:34:33.840
We will also see all of the outputs in the log.

00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:38.919
And in this case, we saw that we had an error.

00:34:40.080 --> 00:34:43.000
It will also highlight both errors and warnings

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:44.800
so that they're very easy to see

00:34:44.800 --> 00:34:46.399
as you scroll through the log.

00:34:47.560 --> 00:34:49.919
And finally, in the end of these logs,

00:34:50.600 --> 00:34:54.040
we always have an expanded session info.

00:34:54.040 --> 00:34:56.000
Now, this session info will include

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:00.520
both session information about the packages

00:35:00.520 --> 00:35:01.879
that we had in the session,

00:35:01.879 --> 00:35:05.800
but also packages that were simply available at the system.

00:35:05.800 --> 00:35:08.879
It will also include options

00:35:08.879 --> 00:35:10.320
that were set in the environment

00:35:10.320 --> 00:35:13.040
and other environment info.

00:35:13.040 --> 00:35:15.399
But that is actually how we execute scripts

00:35:16.320 --> 00:35:19.520
and how we do them in Nominoidisk in general.

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:21.840
But I'll hand it over to Anders.

00:35:21.840 --> 00:35:24.360
And Anders will tell us a bit about

00:35:24.360 --> 00:35:27.320
how we got our colleagues to actually do this.

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:31.520
Yeah, thank you.

00:35:32.800 --> 00:35:33.959
Yeah, so once again,

00:35:35.040 --> 00:35:38.840
the way we have primarily been doing our user support

00:35:38.840 --> 00:35:41.719
and our education is to let everybody know

00:35:41.719 --> 00:35:44.679
that there's help to be made.

00:35:44.679 --> 00:35:47.199
So the help is here.

00:35:47.239 --> 00:35:49.919
So we have primarily been supporting people

00:35:49.919 --> 00:35:52.080
via a one-stop shop website

00:35:53.040 --> 00:35:55.879
that collects all of these package down sites.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:01.120
And recently we have introduced Stack Overflow for Teams

00:36:02.439 --> 00:36:03.959
as a Q&A.

00:36:04.879 --> 00:36:07.959
Until then, we have been using Microsoft Teams,

00:36:07.959 --> 00:36:09.959
we have been using DevOps,

00:36:09.959 --> 00:36:14.959
we have been using plain old mail to do this support.

00:36:15.959 --> 00:36:17.600
In terms of education,

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:21.000
we have promoted self-learning and learning by doing.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:24.520
This has been done through a podcast, as Phil mentioned.

00:36:24.520 --> 00:36:27.719
And we have internal e-learning as well.

00:36:27.719 --> 00:36:29.879
This is built on top of degree.com.

00:36:30.959 --> 00:36:34.040
We also provide lots of external references

00:36:34.040 --> 00:36:36.600
and e-learning to the outside world,

00:36:36.600 --> 00:36:39.199
the ones you can find on the web.

00:36:39.199 --> 00:36:41.159
We have done courses and demos

00:36:41.159 --> 00:36:43.439
on how to get started with R and Novo,

00:36:44.439 --> 00:36:46.479
but it's really the website

00:36:46.479 --> 00:36:48.399
that has been doing the heavy lifting.

00:36:50.080 --> 00:36:53.639
So the website looks like this,

00:36:53.639 --> 00:36:55.719
and we call it the R.doc homepage.

00:36:55.719 --> 00:36:59.000
You simply write R-doc in the browser

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:00.760
when you're on the corporate network

00:37:00.760 --> 00:37:02.479
and you'll be taken to this.

00:37:03.600 --> 00:37:06.399
So it's a one point of entry homepage for everything.

00:37:06.399 --> 00:37:08.760
We have the motto that everything should be here.

00:37:08.760 --> 00:37:10.800
If you cannot find it here, then it should be here

00:37:10.800 --> 00:37:11.800
and we will make it.

00:37:13.760 --> 00:37:17.159
So this site collects all the documentation

00:37:17.159 --> 00:37:19.040
and references just mentioned.

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:23.159
It has the podcast, it has the Pakistan website.

00:37:23.159 --> 00:37:26.280
It has vignettes, long format documentation.

00:37:26.280 --> 00:37:28.679
It has an entire output catalog

00:37:28.679 --> 00:37:33.679
so you can see how a program is structured.

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:35.959
It has lots of guides and more.

00:37:37.520 --> 00:37:40.679
We also link further on to all of these e-learning

00:37:40.679 --> 00:37:42.879
and education sites.

00:37:44.439 --> 00:37:48.120
Something that you all know that is present in R,

00:37:48.120 --> 00:37:50.520
this is not actually a given in other languages

00:37:50.520 --> 00:37:54.800
where you can simply write help in the IDE

00:37:54.800 --> 00:37:57.000
and get the documentation.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:00.280
So we, of course, also convey this to our users.

00:38:00.280 --> 00:38:03.080
And we really try to write high quality documentation

00:38:03.080 --> 00:38:04.159
on our packages.

00:38:05.560 --> 00:38:08.080
So you can get this right away.

00:38:08.080 --> 00:38:11.479
We've also tried to do the equivalent of use this

00:38:11.479 --> 00:38:12.879
in a package called nninit,

00:38:12.879 --> 00:38:14.360
and this will help you get started

00:38:14.360 --> 00:38:16.280
the first time you log in.

00:38:16.280 --> 00:38:19.520
It will help you troubleshoot if you have any problems.

00:38:19.520 --> 00:38:22.600
It will help you initialize and set up stuff,

00:38:22.600 --> 00:38:26.280
trials, repos, new packages,

00:38:26.280 --> 00:38:28.679
just in general, initiating stuff.

00:38:30.159 --> 00:38:32.439
And we have also tried to integrate

00:38:32.439 --> 00:38:34.600
and utilize all the RStudio features

00:38:34.600 --> 00:38:36.800
with add-ins and snippets

00:38:36.800 --> 00:38:39.439
to make them a nicer user experience.

00:38:40.439 --> 00:38:44.520
The podcast is 10 to 15 minutes of how-to's

00:38:44.520 --> 00:38:47.800
of everything from the complex to the very simple.

00:38:47.800 --> 00:38:49.239
How do you get started?

00:38:51.040 --> 00:38:52.600
How do you make your first output?

00:38:52.600 --> 00:38:53.879
That sort of stuff.

00:38:53.879 --> 00:38:56.000
And again, anybody can contribute here.

00:38:59.360 --> 00:39:01.040
The one thing I want to highlight

00:39:01.040 --> 00:39:03.159
is this Stack Overflow for Teams.

00:39:03.159 --> 00:39:06.760
We have just recently rolled this out.

00:39:06.760 --> 00:39:08.399
It's only a month old,

00:39:08.399 --> 00:39:10.080
but we can tell already now

00:39:10.080 --> 00:39:13.040
that it's going to be really good.

00:39:13.040 --> 00:39:15.719
We have already 174 questions

00:39:15.719 --> 00:39:20.719
and 255, sorry, not 55, 25 answers in there

00:39:20.959 --> 00:39:23.679
and 65 daily active users.

00:39:23.679 --> 00:39:26.919
So we really had no good place for Q&A,

00:39:26.919 --> 00:39:28.320
and we wanted to avoid answering

00:39:28.320 --> 00:39:30.120
the same questions again and again.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:34.560
So this site really helps spread the support burden.

00:39:34.560 --> 00:39:36.520
It helps build you a knowledge base,

00:39:36.520 --> 00:39:38.000
and it's not just for code.

00:39:38.719 --> 00:39:41.199
And this is also familiar to all programmers.

00:39:41.199 --> 00:39:45.560
So there's no education for this needed.

00:39:45.560 --> 00:39:49.199
So if we have any regrets in terms of change management,

00:39:49.199 --> 00:39:51.439
it's just that we didn't get this out sooner.

00:39:54.479 --> 00:39:57.360
So now I'll hand it back to Ari,

00:39:57.360 --> 00:39:59.679
and he'll tell you about the submission.

00:40:02.520 --> 00:40:06.399
Now, getting back to what I highlighted in the beginning,

00:40:07.360 --> 00:40:11.040
we've always believed in the power of taking steps

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:13.719
rather than thinking about how big they should be.

00:40:13.719 --> 00:40:17.439
And to put everything in ANOS and CIFN into perspective

00:40:17.439 --> 00:40:19.439
and how you could do all of this

00:40:19.439 --> 00:40:21.320
while doing a drop project,

00:40:21.320 --> 00:40:23.439
we'll just look at a quick timeline

00:40:23.439 --> 00:40:24.679
of the development here.

00:40:25.879 --> 00:40:29.639
So in 2019, we got the commitment to report a trial

00:40:29.639 --> 00:40:31.840
in another language than CES.

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:33.080
In the beginning of 2020,

00:40:33.080 --> 00:40:38.080
we had collected functionalities into two R packages.

00:40:38.360 --> 00:40:39.280
Soon after that,

00:40:39.280 --> 00:40:42.360
we initiated the first R program on this trial,

00:40:42.360 --> 00:40:44.199
chosen to be the first one reported

00:40:44.199 --> 00:40:45.639
in another language than CES.

00:40:49.239 --> 00:40:50.159
And we even did that

00:40:50.159 --> 00:40:53.199
before we had the first workbench in production.

00:40:53.199 --> 00:40:55.719
Unfortunately, the trial got delayed,

00:40:55.719 --> 00:40:57.479
but we were determined to prove

00:40:57.479 --> 00:41:00.439
that we could use R in our deliverables.

00:41:00.439 --> 00:41:04.120
And we did an experiment with learning a DSUR instead.

00:41:05.080 --> 00:41:08.479
Later on in 2020, we split up the functionalities

00:41:08.479 --> 00:41:10.600
and created packages and package shelf

00:41:10.600 --> 00:41:12.239
of everything that was to come.

00:41:13.159 --> 00:41:15.199
And we were working on the documentation

00:41:15.199 --> 00:41:18.800
and released the RDoC homepage in the end of 2020.

00:41:20.120 --> 00:41:21.959
And from doing this DSUR,

00:41:21.959 --> 00:41:24.560
we just learned an incredible amount of stuff

00:41:25.479 --> 00:41:26.879
during our first deliverables.

00:41:26.879 --> 00:41:29.600
So we updated a lot of core functionalities

00:41:29.600 --> 00:41:31.439
and the packages.

00:41:31.439 --> 00:41:33.679
We update the workbench once more

00:41:33.679 --> 00:41:37.360
with load balancing and multiple servers.

00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:39.399
Soon after that,

00:41:39.399 --> 00:41:41.040
I managed to convince our management

00:41:41.040 --> 00:41:44.080
that we're now ready to run phase three trials in R,

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:47.040
and we do the first commits on these trials.

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:48.159
Immediately after that,

00:41:48.159 --> 00:41:52.320
we follow up with five clinical pharmacology trials.

00:41:52.320 --> 00:41:56.800
And finally, right before Christmas in the end of 2021,

00:41:56.800 --> 00:42:01.120
we report our first trial ever in another language than SAS.

00:42:02.320 --> 00:42:05.479
And between 2022 and 2023,

00:42:05.479 --> 00:42:09.080
we just have an incredible amounts of first happening.

00:42:10.120 --> 00:42:12.639
And we also update the workbench once more

00:42:12.639 --> 00:42:15.399
because we're sending so much data in and out of it now

00:42:15.399 --> 00:42:19.360
that it crashes when we run these big add-on programs.

00:42:21.840 --> 00:42:26.239
So what we end up with is a huge package

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:31.280
of R-based GFL programs and some add-on programs in R.

00:42:31.320 --> 00:42:35.040
But basically after we proved in the end of 2020

00:42:35.040 --> 00:42:37.639
that it was possible to deliver a DSUR

00:42:37.639 --> 00:42:41.199
that followed basically all the same processes internally

00:42:41.199 --> 00:42:43.159
as we do for clinical trials,

00:42:43.159 --> 00:42:45.560
we were using R in all project deliverables

00:42:45.560 --> 00:42:46.719
from that point on.

00:42:49.959 --> 00:42:54.280
One thing to note is that we initially did not intend

00:42:54.320 --> 00:42:57.600
to submit all of those R-TFL programs.

00:42:57.600 --> 00:43:00.120
If we look at FDA guidance,

00:43:00.120 --> 00:43:04.320
then our plan was to submit all of our add-on programs,

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:05.840
including those made in R,

00:43:06.800 --> 00:43:10.280
and then having those R-TFL programs internally

00:43:11.199 --> 00:43:14.399
and instead submit our SAS parallel programs

00:43:14.399 --> 00:43:17.639
for our primary and secondary efficacy analysis,

00:43:17.639 --> 00:43:20.560
which is something that we had done in projects before.

00:43:21.560 --> 00:43:24.320
And that leaves us with this gray area

00:43:25.239 --> 00:43:27.840
that we were still creating a strategy for.

00:43:27.840 --> 00:43:30.120
I'll get back to this in just a second.

00:43:32.719 --> 00:43:35.439
The add-on R programs that we submitted,

00:43:35.439 --> 00:43:37.760
they were designed with minimal dependencies

00:43:37.760 --> 00:43:39.320
on internal packages,

00:43:39.320 --> 00:43:41.959
as we weren't sure how to best submit packages

00:43:41.959 --> 00:43:43.719
at this point in time.

00:43:43.719 --> 00:43:46.600
We did use our internal package in an access

00:43:46.600 --> 00:43:48.320
for getting access to data,

00:43:48.399 --> 00:43:50.239
but we didn't plan on submitting it

00:43:50.239 --> 00:43:53.439
just as we didn't submit SAS-based macros

00:43:53.439 --> 00:43:55.080
that only work internally.

00:43:58.239 --> 00:44:01.239
We did still think that we needed to tell authorities

00:44:01.239 --> 00:44:03.000
about abuse of R.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:06.560
So you can see here an excerpt from a type C meeting package

00:44:06.560 --> 00:44:10.560
where we mentioned that we plan on submitting R programs

00:44:10.560 --> 00:44:14.120
and we will specify R-related stuff in the ADHE

00:44:14.120 --> 00:44:16.040
and submit internal packages

00:44:16.040 --> 00:44:18.280
if they are not publicly available.

00:44:19.320 --> 00:44:23.080
In our pre-BLA meeting package,

00:44:23.080 --> 00:44:25.280
we get more specific and we mentioned

00:44:25.280 --> 00:44:29.360
that we intend to use the R package, package light,

00:44:29.360 --> 00:44:32.159
which packages R packages to TXT

00:44:33.439 --> 00:44:35.679
in order to pass them through the submission gateway

00:44:35.679 --> 00:44:36.679
at the FDA.

00:44:38.600 --> 00:44:40.639
And this initial approach is the method used

00:44:40.639 --> 00:44:43.760
by the R Consortium Working Group R for Submission

00:44:43.760 --> 00:44:46.560
in their first pilot submission to FDA.

00:44:47.560 --> 00:44:50.120
We also mirror their approach in the ADHE

00:44:50.120 --> 00:44:53.080
where we add something about R in the standard section

00:44:53.080 --> 00:44:56.080
and we add an additional very short appendix

00:44:56.080 --> 00:44:59.159
on what you would need in order to run the other programs.

00:45:02.320 --> 00:45:04.959
So with this, we bundle everything together

00:45:04.959 --> 00:45:09.479
and we submit our first multilingual submission package

00:45:09.479 --> 00:45:10.320
to FDA.

00:45:12.520 --> 00:45:15.760
But there's still this gray area that we need to tackle

00:45:15.879 --> 00:45:20.560
because we know that PMDA has already made

00:45:20.560 --> 00:45:24.080
pre-submission requests for additional TFL programs.

00:45:24.080 --> 00:45:26.280
And we know that it's not unusual for FDA

00:45:26.280 --> 00:45:27.760
or other health authorities

00:45:27.760 --> 00:45:30.280
to ask for additional programs.

00:45:31.800 --> 00:45:34.320
And lo and behold, it doesn't take long

00:45:34.320 --> 00:45:36.040
until we receive this.

00:45:38.040 --> 00:45:41.159
An information request from FDA stating,

00:45:41.159 --> 00:45:44.239
to facilitate the efficiency of the safety review,

00:45:44.239 --> 00:45:47.040
submit all programming codes used to create

00:45:47.040 --> 00:45:49.239
the tables and figures in the ISS

00:45:49.239 --> 00:45:51.399
and the safety sections of the CSRs.

00:45:52.399 --> 00:45:56.520
And now we're thinking, Chip, it's real.

00:45:57.439 --> 00:45:59.280
We really need to figure this out

00:45:59.280 --> 00:46:01.600
and we only have 10 days to do it.

00:46:03.159 --> 00:46:06.000
You can imagine the stressed looks on our faces

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:09.080
and a lot of deep breaths that need to be taken

00:46:09.080 --> 00:46:10.919
at this point in time.

00:46:10.919 --> 00:46:14.560
But after we have calmed ourselves down a bit,

00:46:14.560 --> 00:46:15.719
we get to it.

00:46:16.639 --> 00:46:19.080
So we knew all trials have been executed

00:46:19.080 --> 00:46:21.120
with the RENV setup.

00:46:21.120 --> 00:46:24.959
So we could use the RENV log files to look up versions

00:46:24.959 --> 00:46:26.959
of all of the internal packages.

00:46:27.959 --> 00:46:31.760
We then use PackageLite to take the package sources

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:38.000
and repackage them all into a single PackageLite file

00:46:38.280 --> 00:46:39.199
for each trial.

00:46:41.919 --> 00:46:46.159
In the submission, we now included the PackageLite file,

00:46:46.159 --> 00:46:49.760
the RENV log file package to text

00:46:49.760 --> 00:46:53.520
and modify to use MRAN for public packages.

00:46:53.520 --> 00:46:57.959
We include RENV's activate script that bootstraps RENV.

00:46:58.919 --> 00:47:02.239
And then a script that would unpack source packages,

00:47:02.239 --> 00:47:06.199
set up a seller for RENV, rebuild the packages

00:47:06.199 --> 00:47:09.959
and initialize an R project with the RENV setup

00:47:10.080 --> 00:47:12.159
and within a dedicated folder structure

00:47:12.159 --> 00:47:15.360
such that all of the internal Novo packages could run.

00:47:18.439 --> 00:47:22.560
In the ADHE, we update the appendix

00:47:22.560 --> 00:47:25.479
to include some information on these new files

00:47:25.479 --> 00:47:27.639
that we're submitting and which commands were needed

00:47:27.639 --> 00:47:30.840
to restore the environment and how you could modify

00:47:30.840 --> 00:47:34.560
the NN access function in order to make it run

00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:36.000
in a local R project.

00:47:36.600 --> 00:47:37.919
So we bundle all of this together

00:47:37.919 --> 00:47:41.800
and ship a whole bunch of R-based TFL programs

00:47:41.800 --> 00:47:43.800
together with the R packages

00:47:43.800 --> 00:47:47.719
and these additional files to the FDA.

00:47:47.719 --> 00:47:50.000
And again, I mean, at this point in time,

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:52.199
we're on top of the world.

00:47:52.199 --> 00:47:53.040
I mean, we did it.

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:54.760
Now we also submitted packages

00:47:54.760 --> 00:47:56.560
and even within this deadline.

00:47:57.600 --> 00:48:02.600
But FDA returns again and they can't get it to work.

00:48:02.639 --> 00:48:04.959
And now we're really thinking, shit.

00:48:05.879 --> 00:48:07.080
And together with that message,

00:48:07.080 --> 00:48:10.080
they also include the following in the information request.

00:48:10.959 --> 00:48:13.600
Submit R code for all safety analysis

00:48:13.600 --> 00:48:16.520
with as minimal package dependency as possible

00:48:16.520 --> 00:48:20.040
and no dependencies to R packages developed internally

00:48:20.040 --> 00:48:21.080
by Novo Nordisk.

00:48:22.239 --> 00:48:24.040
And now we're really thinking, shit.

00:48:26.120 --> 00:48:27.919
At this point in time, we're doubting

00:48:27.919 --> 00:48:29.639
if we can get it to work.

00:48:30.639 --> 00:48:31.600
At this point in time,

00:48:31.600 --> 00:48:34.120
we're doubting everything that you heard

00:48:34.120 --> 00:48:36.159
up until now in this presentation.

00:48:36.159 --> 00:48:39.800
The package strategy, the submission strategy,

00:48:39.800 --> 00:48:42.479
the future of R at Novo Nordisk.

00:48:42.479 --> 00:48:46.360
We poured so much energy into making this a reality

00:48:46.360 --> 00:48:48.479
and now we're at this pivotal moment

00:48:48.479 --> 00:48:51.639
where we make it or we break it.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:55.080
They can't restart the environment

00:48:55.080 --> 00:48:58.360
and they want us to reprogram all the programs.

00:48:58.360 --> 00:48:59.320
So what do we do?

00:49:01.479 --> 00:49:05.159
We do something we very, very rarely do.

00:49:05.159 --> 00:49:07.959
We invite FDA for an informal meeting.

00:49:10.479 --> 00:49:14.280
In the meantime, we go back looking at our build script

00:49:14.280 --> 00:49:16.399
and optimize it once more.

00:49:16.399 --> 00:49:21.199
We also optimize the R and V log file

00:49:21.199 --> 00:49:23.879
to use Posit's public package manager

00:49:23.879 --> 00:49:26.800
as at this point in time, MRAN has now shut down.

00:49:29.360 --> 00:49:33.760
We write a very long and very detailed instruction

00:49:33.760 --> 00:49:36.560
with screenshots of everything that's happening

00:49:36.560 --> 00:49:38.120
and what you should expect to see

00:49:38.120 --> 00:49:40.159
when you're restoring the environment,

00:49:40.159 --> 00:49:43.479
when you're executing different parts of the scripts.

00:49:43.479 --> 00:49:46.280
And we ship this off to FDA before the meeting,

00:49:46.280 --> 00:49:48.719
hoping that we now have done it right.

00:49:51.080 --> 00:49:53.639
Now this meeting happened quite recently

00:49:53.639 --> 00:49:57.520
and minutes before the meeting, we are quite nervous.

00:49:58.919 --> 00:50:00.320
Like what are they gonna say?

00:50:00.320 --> 00:50:01.800
Are we going to be grilled?

00:50:02.800 --> 00:50:04.840
And the meeting starts and it turns out

00:50:04.840 --> 00:50:08.639
they now have been successful in restoring the environment.

00:50:08.639 --> 00:50:10.719
And we were just thinking, yes.

00:50:11.639 --> 00:50:13.679
And they bring up the programs and mentioned

00:50:13.679 --> 00:50:15.919
that part of the reason for them asking

00:50:17.439 --> 00:50:19.600
is that it gives FDA an opportunity

00:50:19.600 --> 00:50:23.840
to see how code inside and outside of packages are built.

00:50:23.840 --> 00:50:27.239
And this would be a great learning opportunity for FDA.

00:50:28.639 --> 00:50:31.000
The statistical revenues in the meeting with FDA

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:32.600
are just so super nice.

00:50:32.600 --> 00:50:36.120
And we realized one very important thing from this meeting.

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:40.080
Submissions in R is new to us,

00:50:40.080 --> 00:50:43.479
but it's definitely new to FDA as well.

00:50:48.080 --> 00:50:50.000
And this brings us to the future

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:51.840
where we have three main points

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:53.520
that we wanna dive deeper into.

00:50:53.520 --> 00:50:56.360
We wanna have a stronger R dedication.

00:50:56.360 --> 00:50:59.040
We want improvements to recreating environments

00:50:59.040 --> 00:51:01.239
outside of the in-and-outs.

00:51:01.239 --> 00:51:04.120
And we wanna fully embrace the open source.

00:51:05.120 --> 00:51:07.000
As part of the R dedication,

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:10.760
we have multiple fully R-based projects already started

00:51:10.760 --> 00:51:13.919
and now also dedicated teams to support our package

00:51:13.919 --> 00:51:15.479
and system development.

00:51:17.080 --> 00:51:20.959
We have learned some very valuable environment lessons

00:51:20.959 --> 00:51:25.040
around the rebuilding across operating systems.

00:51:25.040 --> 00:51:28.320
And the fact that the official package manager

00:51:28.320 --> 00:51:30.600
stored binaries of packages

00:51:30.600 --> 00:51:33.080
was really invaluable in this submission

00:51:33.080 --> 00:51:35.520
as we didn't need to compile from a source

00:51:35.520 --> 00:51:36.840
on Windows machines.

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:39.280
And we already have many ideas

00:51:39.280 --> 00:51:42.800
for how we can work tests around this into our workflows

00:51:42.800 --> 00:51:45.600
and also guide colleagues and peers

00:51:45.600 --> 00:51:47.760
for regulatory interaction.

00:51:47.760 --> 00:51:51.760
And last but not least, fully embrace open source.

00:51:52.560 --> 00:51:55.959
The cleanup of all of our internal packages will start soon

00:51:55.959 --> 00:52:00.439
and we will move towards open development on GitHub.

00:52:00.439 --> 00:52:03.040
We will rebuild a lot of our core functionalities

00:52:03.040 --> 00:52:06.679
such that it will work for the broader programming community

00:52:06.679 --> 00:52:08.800
and aim to get our packages onto CRAN

00:52:08.800 --> 00:52:11.719
and dive much deeper into FarmReverse.

00:52:14.479 --> 00:52:18.360
Before we end, I really wanna acknowledge

00:52:18.360 --> 00:52:21.199
all the package contributors and system contributors

00:52:21.199 --> 00:52:24.080
that we have, the programmers and statisticians

00:52:24.080 --> 00:52:26.679
that fought to learn R on these trials

00:52:26.679 --> 00:52:29.439
throughout a very hectic time,

00:52:29.439 --> 00:52:32.840
the invaluable input and knowledge coming from our peers

00:52:32.840 --> 00:52:36.120
at other companies working with our working groups

00:52:36.120 --> 00:52:38.639
under our consortium, the R validation hub

00:52:38.639 --> 00:52:40.760
and all the efforts going into making

00:52:40.760 --> 00:52:42.280
something like this possible.

00:52:43.280 --> 00:52:44.959
We would also like to acknowledge the fact

00:52:44.959 --> 00:52:47.679
that FDA agreed to meet with us

00:52:47.679 --> 00:52:49.879
and advertise in the end of the day.

00:52:49.919 --> 00:52:54.040
It's also just nice, normal people working at FDA.

00:52:54.040 --> 00:52:56.560
They are much more open and welcoming of R

00:52:56.560 --> 00:52:58.360
than we anticipated.

00:52:58.360 --> 00:53:02.120
And we encourage that you reach out just as we did.

00:53:02.120 --> 00:53:05.800
So thank you so much for listening to our presentation.

00:53:13.399 --> 00:53:14.679
Awesome.

00:53:14.679 --> 00:53:15.639
Thank you, Novo team.

00:53:15.639 --> 00:53:17.439
That was fantastic.

00:53:17.439 --> 00:53:20.080
Gosh, what a aid this is gonna be

00:53:20.080 --> 00:53:22.800
for other pharmas going down this path.

00:53:23.719 --> 00:53:27.560
We have more questions than I think we have time for.

00:53:27.560 --> 00:53:29.360
So we're gonna tackle a few of them.

00:53:29.360 --> 00:53:32.040
And they also came in at different times

00:53:32.040 --> 00:53:35.959
before you had got to that point later on

00:53:35.959 --> 00:53:36.840
in the presentation.

00:53:36.840 --> 00:53:38.399
So if you think we've already tackled it,

00:53:38.399 --> 00:53:39.239
just let me know.

00:53:39.239 --> 00:53:42.040
But I'm gonna go based off of popularity

00:53:42.040 --> 00:53:44.919
and we've got 30 plus questions.

00:53:44.919 --> 00:53:46.439
So let's tackle a few of them.

00:53:47.760 --> 00:53:51.399
And so let's start off with this first one.

00:53:51.399 --> 00:53:53.439
How can we ensure that R code,

00:53:53.439 --> 00:53:57.439
including internal R packages is responsible,

00:53:57.439 --> 00:54:00.399
is reproducible on a reviewer's machine,

00:54:00.399 --> 00:54:02.439
such as that of the FDA?

00:54:05.679 --> 00:54:06.959
That is a very good question.

00:54:06.959 --> 00:54:08.120
Would you take it Stan?

00:54:09.760 --> 00:54:11.719
Yes, so that is a good question.

00:54:11.719 --> 00:54:14.399
And of course we cannot completely ensure it.

00:54:15.280 --> 00:54:18.800
What we can ensure is that we can reproduce the environment

00:54:18.800 --> 00:54:21.320
such that they have the same packages available,

00:54:21.320 --> 00:54:23.560
the same version of R available,

00:54:23.560 --> 00:54:27.479
that they, in that way we can make sure

00:54:27.479 --> 00:54:30.360
that they have data in the places

00:54:30.360 --> 00:54:32.199
we would like them to have data in.

00:54:32.199 --> 00:54:34.959
And that way use our programs.

00:54:35.840 --> 00:54:37.679
And that was what we did in the scripts

00:54:37.679 --> 00:54:39.080
that we sent to them now,

00:54:39.080 --> 00:54:42.919
was to actually from the file that we have submitted

00:54:42.919 --> 00:54:45.679
in this M5 folder structure,

00:54:45.679 --> 00:54:49.600
make it possible to recreate the entire folder structure

00:54:49.600 --> 00:54:51.760
that we normally work upon,

00:54:51.760 --> 00:54:54.879
and then reuse the in an access facility

00:54:54.879 --> 00:54:56.840
and in a biostat functionality

00:54:56.840 --> 00:54:59.439
to ensure that the packages that they have loaded

00:54:59.439 --> 00:55:02.959
is the same as what we are seeing.

00:55:04.719 --> 00:55:09.080
And thereby be very close to a fact

00:55:09.080 --> 00:55:11.560
that they will get the same result as us,

00:55:11.560 --> 00:55:12.719
as close as we can get.

00:55:13.919 --> 00:55:15.439
Fantastic.

00:55:15.439 --> 00:55:18.639
Anybody else on the NOVA team want to mention, comment?

00:55:20.320 --> 00:55:22.120
No, I think that's sufficient.

00:55:22.120 --> 00:55:23.239
Yeah, I think that's enough.

00:55:23.239 --> 00:55:25.439
All right, so let's go to another question here.

00:55:25.439 --> 00:55:27.679
So the next question says,

00:55:27.679 --> 00:55:31.000
how long before it becomes a common practice in NOVA

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:34.239
to use R for trial related programming?

00:55:37.399 --> 00:55:40.439
So I think, well, so I mean,

00:55:41.080 --> 00:55:45.639
I think doing this one drug project at first

00:55:45.639 --> 00:55:47.679
has really kind of kicked off

00:55:47.679 --> 00:55:50.199
like an internal revolution for doing this

00:55:50.199 --> 00:55:54.239
because we proved that it was possible to do it.

00:55:54.239 --> 00:55:56.399
It's been hard and difficult

00:55:56.399 --> 00:55:58.879
and there's a lot of change management involved,

00:55:58.879 --> 00:56:02.439
but the benefits we've seen from this,

00:56:02.439 --> 00:56:07.159
like reusing TFL objects into result meeting slides,

00:56:07.159 --> 00:56:08.719
like all the benefits we get

00:56:08.719 --> 00:56:11.479
from doing HTML based stuff now

00:56:11.479 --> 00:56:14.479
is just spilling over into other projects.

00:56:14.479 --> 00:56:17.159
I think probably we're closing in

00:56:17.159 --> 00:56:22.159
on maybe 30, 40% of the trials now are starting up in R.

00:56:24.159 --> 00:56:29.159
And we have, I think 115 trials ongoing currently.

00:56:31.800 --> 00:56:34.679
So the uptake is quite big.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:38.959
Fantastic.

00:56:38.959 --> 00:56:40.199
Any other comments?

00:56:41.560 --> 00:56:43.239
Let's jump to the next one.

00:56:43.239 --> 00:56:44.919
All right, so the next one is about

00:56:44.919 --> 00:56:47.679
the scope of the undertaking.

00:56:47.679 --> 00:56:50.080
How many personnel are needed to maintain

00:56:50.080 --> 00:56:52.239
the complexity of this environment?

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:56.399
Will you take that, Stefan?

00:56:57.439 --> 00:56:59.959
Yeah, so that's a hard question also

00:57:01.439 --> 00:57:03.080
because at NOVA we noticed this

00:57:03.080 --> 00:57:06.280
has really been a bottom up adventure

00:57:06.280 --> 00:57:08.800
where we saw from the top

00:57:08.800 --> 00:57:12.679
that we would like us to make this report

00:57:12.679 --> 00:57:14.479
or trial in another language than R.

00:57:18.399 --> 00:57:21.639
And then we were pretty much allowed to run with it.

00:57:23.879 --> 00:57:27.520
So we've been a few people working on the packages.

00:57:27.520 --> 00:57:32.120
I would guess six that would do usual commits.

00:57:32.120 --> 00:57:35.120
We have been mainly three

00:57:35.120 --> 00:57:37.560
to work on the statistical computing environment.

00:57:39.120 --> 00:57:40.959
In terms of the actual development of it,

00:57:40.959 --> 00:57:44.080
we had way more in terms of getting it GXP validated

00:57:45.320 --> 00:57:48.560
because that's just a much, much bigger adventure.

00:57:49.679 --> 00:57:51.479
But in terms of active development.

00:57:53.879 --> 00:57:58.120
And then how many for actual trial conduct?

00:57:58.120 --> 00:58:00.639
I mean, there's been a very steep learning curve

00:58:02.399 --> 00:58:03.239
on the trial.

00:58:03.239 --> 00:58:06.280
So I would say there's anything between

00:58:08.080 --> 00:58:11.000
30, 40, 50 programmers and statisticians

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:14.479
that have been running all of these trials,

00:58:14.479 --> 00:58:15.879
creating R programs.

00:58:16.760 --> 00:58:19.560
I must say all the trials have been running in parallel,

00:58:19.560 --> 00:58:23.199
which has also made the workload quite a lot bigger.

00:58:24.080 --> 00:58:26.600
But a lot of people have been involved

00:58:26.600 --> 00:58:28.600
in doing actual trial conduct.

00:58:29.959 --> 00:58:31.360
Yeah.

00:58:31.360 --> 00:58:33.280
And one thing I think we need to add

00:58:33.280 --> 00:58:38.280
is also that as we do it internally open source,

00:58:39.159 --> 00:58:41.840
lots of people step up and contribute.

00:58:41.840 --> 00:58:45.560
The podcast, for example, is somebody came up with that

00:58:45.560 --> 00:58:47.000
and we said, go with it.

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:49.600
Let's put it on this RDocs thing.

00:58:49.600 --> 00:58:51.600
The same with this DeGreed.

00:58:51.600 --> 00:58:53.800
Another guy came up with that.

00:58:53.800 --> 00:58:56.000
And so we just grabbed those balls

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:59.959
and we really try to encourage our users

00:58:59.959 --> 00:59:04.959
and our friends to do that sort of thing.

00:59:05.399 --> 00:59:10.280
So it's hard to put in terms of FTEs

00:59:11.800 --> 00:59:14.040
because we can't, we don't know actually.

00:59:15.280 --> 00:59:17.520
And on that point, that's what's been a learning

00:59:17.520 --> 00:59:20.919
for us who have been developing the packages first

00:59:20.919 --> 00:59:23.479
to actually start to let go

00:59:23.479 --> 00:59:26.919
and let the community be the main drivers.

00:59:26.919 --> 00:59:29.760
So for instance, for this table package that we have,

00:59:30.520 --> 00:59:32.320
we're getting more and more contributors around the company

00:59:32.320 --> 00:59:36.239
for features that they would like it to include.

00:59:36.239 --> 00:59:37.719
And also feature requests, of course,

00:59:37.719 --> 00:59:41.919
that's why can't I use the DT package directly from this?

00:59:41.919 --> 00:59:44.639
So we will of course start to implement that

00:59:44.639 --> 00:59:47.919
so that it has full support for that as well.

00:59:50.159 --> 00:59:51.000
Interesting.

00:59:51.000 --> 00:59:53.600
So I've got a couple more questions.

00:59:53.600 --> 00:59:57.080
So I'm gonna go a little bit faster on these

00:59:57.520 --> 01:00:00.040
because we've got a lot of people still on.

01:00:00.040 --> 01:00:01.520
So let's keep going.

01:00:01.520 --> 01:00:03.399
So this next one said,

01:00:03.399 --> 01:00:05.760
what can you clarify by what you mean

01:00:05.760 --> 01:00:08.040
by first R-based submission?

01:00:09.679 --> 01:00:13.600
It says, are all the programs in code were in R?

01:00:14.679 --> 01:00:18.399
Yeah, so all of the tables, figures and listings

01:00:18.399 --> 01:00:20.399
that we've made have all been in R.

01:00:21.280 --> 01:00:26.280
So at Novo, we have been using a data set

01:00:27.239 --> 01:00:29.479
for analysis results for quite some time,

01:00:29.479 --> 01:00:31.800
meaning that the statistical analysis

01:00:31.800 --> 01:00:34.800
are still done in SAS, put into a huge data set

01:00:34.800 --> 01:00:38.560
and then reported through our TFL programs.

01:00:38.560 --> 01:00:41.439
So statistical analysis are still onto the side,

01:00:41.439 --> 01:00:43.280
onto and into SAS,

01:00:44.719 --> 01:00:47.560
but everything else in regards to TFL

01:00:47.560 --> 01:00:50.520
have been developed in R.

01:00:50.520 --> 01:00:52.520
And then as well, we have some of these

01:00:53.479 --> 01:00:55.760
R-based atom programs,

01:00:55.760 --> 01:00:58.000
which have primarily been for the data set

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:01.399
where we just need the additional compute power

01:01:01.399 --> 01:01:03.600
that we can get from being in the cloud

01:01:03.600 --> 01:01:06.320
because they have been extremely huge.

01:01:09.439 --> 01:01:10.800
Awesome, another question.

01:01:10.800 --> 01:01:15.280
What were the business benefits of an R solution

01:01:15.280 --> 01:01:20.280
relative to commercials or for example, SAS?

01:01:22.560 --> 01:01:24.000
That's a good question.

01:01:25.760 --> 01:01:28.879
I guess, so like Stefan said, this spills over

01:01:28.879 --> 01:01:30.399
or I believe it's UI.

01:01:30.399 --> 01:01:32.959
It spills over in all sorts of other things.

01:01:32.959 --> 01:01:37.959
So when we do presentation slides or we do other stuff,

01:01:39.040 --> 01:01:40.719
it's much more easy to pick up

01:01:40.719 --> 01:01:45.120
and do something more powerful with these shiny apps

01:01:45.120 --> 01:01:45.959
and so on.

01:01:45.959 --> 01:01:47.879
They also can utilize the packages

01:01:47.879 --> 01:01:51.840
so we can kind of, again, build up functionality.

01:01:52.959 --> 01:01:54.560
So it really spills over,

01:01:54.639 --> 01:01:56.679
but again, it's impossible to say,

01:01:56.679 --> 01:02:01.479
like in terms of money, how much again it is,

01:02:01.479 --> 01:02:04.959
but we see it kind of starting to permeate

01:02:04.959 --> 01:02:09.959
into other non-GXP tasks and other stuff that we do.

01:02:11.439 --> 01:02:13.760
And one other very important aspect

01:02:13.760 --> 01:02:16.080
from the business side has been

01:02:16.080 --> 01:02:20.080
how do we get more employees involved in biostatistics?

01:02:20.080 --> 01:02:22.199
Because we are doing more and more trials,

01:02:22.199 --> 01:02:24.000
so we need more and more employees.

01:02:25.520 --> 01:02:28.840
And here we have seen that there are just so many more

01:02:28.840 --> 01:02:31.280
people we can get who know R

01:02:31.280 --> 01:02:35.479
than there are actually people coming out who know SAS.

01:02:35.479 --> 01:02:38.080
So from a business benefits,

01:02:38.080 --> 01:02:40.959
I would say one of the highest values

01:02:40.959 --> 01:02:44.919
is getting new employees and getting them up to speed fast.

01:02:46.040 --> 01:02:46.879
Definitely.

01:02:47.879 --> 01:02:51.479
So you just mentioned research and other areas.

01:02:52.360 --> 01:02:54.520
And for the late stage here, a question that comes up,

01:02:54.520 --> 01:02:56.600
I think a lot of people are wondering about

01:02:56.600 --> 01:03:00.239
is do you plan to use Python in a submission too?

01:03:00.239 --> 01:03:02.600
And does your scientific

01:03:02.600 --> 01:03:06.560
or statistical computing environment support Python

01:03:06.560 --> 01:03:08.879
and R development and apps?

01:03:10.439 --> 01:03:11.280
Yeah.

01:03:13.120 --> 01:03:15.399
We have Python on the system.

01:03:15.520 --> 01:03:19.520
It is an experimental feature, if you will.

01:03:19.520 --> 01:03:21.560
So, and as far as I know,

01:03:21.560 --> 01:03:26.399
we don't have any plans for doing Python-based submissions,

01:03:26.399 --> 01:03:28.719
but we feel that there is a pressure.

01:03:28.719 --> 01:03:31.959
So the users or some users really want that as well.

01:03:32.840 --> 01:03:35.679
So now we are trying to come up with similar strategies

01:03:35.679 --> 01:03:38.399
for handling Python so that,

01:03:38.399 --> 01:03:41.600
so you can really have a true multilingual system.

01:03:42.600 --> 01:03:46.239
But we have seen, we have started the process,

01:03:46.239 --> 01:03:49.879
but it is a bit harder with Python than R

01:03:49.879 --> 01:03:52.600
because we don't have CRAN,

01:03:53.760 --> 01:03:57.800
where we have a much, much better control.

01:03:57.800 --> 01:04:00.679
And we know that the packages are tested together.

01:04:00.679 --> 01:04:02.679
So we can have this nice strategy

01:04:02.679 --> 01:04:04.679
for how we put the packages in,

01:04:04.679 --> 01:04:06.040
where we know that these packages

01:04:06.040 --> 01:04:08.040
are going to function together.

01:04:08.040 --> 01:04:09.800
That doesn't really apply to Python.

01:04:09.800 --> 01:04:13.840
So that is at least the problem

01:04:13.840 --> 01:04:17.840
that we are tackling right now in order to do it.

01:04:19.639 --> 01:04:20.479
Awesome.

01:04:20.479 --> 01:04:22.159
How about one more question here?

01:04:23.479 --> 01:04:27.560
How often do you update your different R environments?

01:04:31.280 --> 01:04:36.280
Yeah, so we've been doing,

01:04:36.439 --> 01:04:37.919
I guess if we even them out,

01:04:38.040 --> 01:04:40.040
it would be like a half yearly update.

01:04:41.760 --> 01:04:44.879
But it has depended on how big are the features

01:04:44.879 --> 01:04:46.679
that we're working on.

01:04:46.679 --> 01:04:49.520
Quite recently, we had a large gap between them

01:04:49.520 --> 01:04:51.959
because we were working on this Kubernetes cluster.

01:04:51.959 --> 01:04:53.879
So that was sort of a big thing.

01:04:53.879 --> 01:04:56.040
We needed to develop the Kubernetes cluster

01:04:56.040 --> 01:04:59.159
and also get it DXP approved

01:04:59.159 --> 01:05:01.959
before we could release it to the broader community.

01:05:01.959 --> 01:05:04.320
So there we had, I think, almost a year.

01:05:04.560 --> 01:05:07.800
But usually it would be about every half yearly.

01:05:07.800 --> 01:05:09.760
And then we have a commitment,

01:05:09.760 --> 01:05:11.919
both in terms of user request,

01:05:11.919 --> 01:05:14.560
but also for ourself,

01:05:14.560 --> 01:05:18.199
that we really want to go down to every second month

01:05:18.199 --> 01:05:20.120
to have updates of the system

01:05:21.120 --> 01:05:23.959
so that new packages can get to users

01:05:23.959 --> 01:05:26.439
much, much faster than they do now.

01:05:29.600 --> 01:05:32.399
And also, I mean, if we're diving more into

01:05:32.439 --> 01:05:34.639
open source, where the release cycle,

01:05:34.639 --> 01:05:37.239
at least from the stuff we see in farmer versus

01:05:37.239 --> 01:05:41.000
is quite fast, like we need to be up to speed

01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:43.800
if we want to include like the latest updates

01:05:43.800 --> 01:05:45.120
into our trials as well.

01:05:45.120 --> 01:05:49.320
So we really want to get the release cycle down.

01:05:49.320 --> 01:05:50.159
Exactly.

01:05:50.159 --> 01:05:51.840
But one thing though,

01:05:53.280 --> 01:05:56.080
even though we have a rather strict package management

01:05:56.080 --> 01:05:59.439
strategy, we have made it so that all users

01:05:59.840 --> 01:06:03.840
can actually, if they work a little bit for it, not much,

01:06:03.840 --> 01:06:05.919
but just change the repository,

01:06:05.919 --> 01:06:08.080
the options repost argument,

01:06:08.080 --> 01:06:11.280
then they can lock themselves into a newer version

01:06:11.280 --> 01:06:14.560
of the packages and start working from there.

01:06:14.560 --> 01:06:15.639
So it is possible.

01:06:15.639 --> 01:06:18.879
And we do have some projects that are starting to do that

01:06:18.879 --> 01:06:22.479
if they feel that the system has fallen a bit too much

01:06:22.479 --> 01:06:25.800
behind that we need to work with the newer packages

01:06:25.800 --> 01:06:28.399
available, and we need to make sure that

01:06:28.399 --> 01:06:29.479
the new package is available,

01:06:29.479 --> 01:06:30.919
then we have shown them, okay,

01:06:30.919 --> 01:06:34.600
how can you do that yourself and still ensure

01:06:34.600 --> 01:06:36.199
that you are compliant?

01:06:38.959 --> 01:06:40.679
So my team just mentioned that we still have a lot

01:06:40.679 --> 01:06:41.520
of people on.

01:06:41.520 --> 01:06:43.320
So if you have some time, let's keep going.

01:06:43.320 --> 01:06:44.199
What the heck, right?

01:06:44.199 --> 01:06:46.520
The questions keep flooding in.

01:06:46.520 --> 01:06:47.360
How about this one?

01:06:47.360 --> 01:06:48.320
I like this.

01:06:48.320 --> 01:06:50.919
So for your next R-based submission,

01:06:50.919 --> 01:06:52.760
what are some things you might do differently

01:06:52.760 --> 01:06:53.800
that jump out to you?

01:06:54.800 --> 01:06:58.199
I think one thing is, I mean,

01:06:58.199 --> 01:07:03.199
we realized now that a statistical reviewer at FDA

01:07:05.280 --> 01:07:10.280
or another health authorities might not have adequate time

01:07:10.280 --> 01:07:15.280
to kind of get acquainted with a whole set of packages

01:07:15.280 --> 01:07:16.479
that's being submitted.

01:07:17.560 --> 01:07:21.360
Meaning that if you're building like super smart

01:07:21.399 --> 01:07:24.600
functionality in a lot of packages and they all like

01:07:24.600 --> 01:07:28.199
really work well together, getting that kind of thrown

01:07:28.199 --> 01:07:31.000
in the face as a reviewer might be too much

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:34.439
and you wouldn't have time to dive deeper into it.

01:07:34.439 --> 01:07:37.919
So we're thinking of a lot of ways of how do we expose

01:07:37.919 --> 01:07:40.000
like the derivations, the calculations,

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:43.840
the analysis that we're doing in programs,

01:07:43.840 --> 01:07:48.360
either through like better logs or kind of surfacing

01:07:48.719 --> 01:07:53.719
more of like the deep based derivations that we're doing.

01:07:54.239 --> 01:07:57.679
And then, I mean, we want to do a submission

01:07:57.679 --> 01:07:59.439
with the Admiral as well.

01:07:59.439 --> 01:08:02.919
We want to use more of these farm roast packages in them.

01:08:05.399 --> 01:08:08.600
And definitely, as I mentioned here,

01:08:08.600 --> 01:08:12.399
testing in a Windows-based operating system

01:08:12.399 --> 01:08:15.000
is something we will definitely be building

01:08:15.080 --> 01:08:17.319
into kind of our submission pipeline

01:08:17.319 --> 01:08:20.279
that it is something that just needs to work.

01:08:21.839 --> 01:08:22.680
So, yeah.

01:08:24.839 --> 01:08:25.680
Fantastic.

01:08:25.680 --> 01:08:26.520
All right.

01:08:26.520 --> 01:08:29.720
How about two more and then I officially

01:08:29.720 --> 01:08:31.600
will end the webinar for today.

01:08:31.600 --> 01:08:34.520
So how about given the significant overlap

01:08:34.520 --> 01:08:37.720
between the responsibilities and functions of IT

01:08:37.720 --> 01:08:40.560
and Biostats, how was collaboration

01:08:40.560 --> 01:08:43.279
between these two sectors?

01:08:43.319 --> 01:08:44.160
Facilitated?

01:08:47.520 --> 01:08:48.359
Definitely.

01:08:48.359 --> 01:08:49.200
Yes.

01:08:49.200 --> 01:08:54.200
And there is actually a good example of this.

01:08:54.520 --> 01:08:59.520
We, at the very first time, the IT development

01:08:59.520 --> 01:09:02.080
sort of developed an R server

01:09:02.080 --> 01:09:05.200
without so much response from Biostatistics.

01:09:06.839 --> 01:09:09.319
And in that server, we said, you can go here

01:09:09.319 --> 01:09:10.720
and you can start programming.

01:09:10.759 --> 01:09:13.839
We said, you can go here and you can start programming.

01:09:13.839 --> 01:09:15.879
And the first thing I tried was,

01:09:15.879 --> 01:09:17.879
okay, so I want to install Tidyverse

01:09:17.879 --> 01:09:19.479
so that I could get going.

01:09:21.040 --> 01:09:22.080
That won't work here.

01:09:22.080 --> 01:09:24.720
We don't have all of these things installed in the system

01:09:24.720 --> 01:09:26.720
so that you can actually do that.

01:09:26.720 --> 01:09:28.120
And okay.

01:09:28.120 --> 01:09:30.680
So I can't even use Tidyverse.

01:09:31.759 --> 01:09:34.919
This is going to be a steep climb

01:09:34.919 --> 01:09:37.120
if we're going to use Base R for everything.

01:09:38.120 --> 01:09:40.080
So from that day,

01:09:40.080 --> 01:09:43.120
we started a really, really close collaboration

01:09:43.120 --> 01:09:44.919
because we sort of saw the need

01:09:44.919 --> 01:09:49.600
that even though you know everything about IT,

01:09:49.600 --> 01:09:52.080
you might not know all the needs

01:09:52.080 --> 01:09:55.240
that there are for an R-based system.

01:09:55.240 --> 01:09:58.799
So from there, we would have both R developers

01:09:58.799 --> 01:10:02.279
and IT developers working closely together,

01:10:02.279 --> 01:10:06.520
ensuring that we would have the best system possible

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:08.000
for the end user.

01:10:09.279 --> 01:10:10.120
Yeah.

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:13.240
Okay, last question.

01:10:13.240 --> 01:10:15.080
This is it, I promise.

01:10:15.080 --> 01:10:17.759
How about, you know, one thing we hear a lot

01:10:17.759 --> 01:10:20.040
about are other regulatory agencies

01:10:20.040 --> 01:10:22.600
besides the FDA for submissions.

01:10:22.600 --> 01:10:24.640
So someone says, can you share about your experience

01:10:24.640 --> 01:10:26.799
with R submissions outside of the FDA,

01:10:26.799 --> 01:10:29.080
EMA, PMDA, et cetera?

01:10:31.080 --> 01:10:34.919
Yeah, so I really want to bring up an example

01:10:34.919 --> 01:10:39.359
from the R Consortium working group, R for Submission,

01:10:39.359 --> 01:10:43.200
where we also tried to reach out to PMDA

01:10:43.200 --> 01:10:46.240
through some of our peers

01:10:46.240 --> 01:10:50.000
in the Japanese Pharmaceutical Manufacturing Association,

01:10:50.000 --> 01:10:51.160
JPMA.

01:10:51.160 --> 01:10:55.200
And the message we got back from PMDA

01:10:55.200 --> 01:10:59.200
was that they didn't feel a need for a pilot submission

01:10:59.200 --> 01:11:02.839
because they already accepted our submissions.

01:11:03.439 --> 01:11:06.720
And what we have still included

01:11:06.720 --> 01:11:11.720
in our correspondences with the PMDA, for instance,

01:11:12.399 --> 01:11:14.399
that we're using R for different stuff,

01:11:14.399 --> 01:11:18.200
we're giving them flow charts of stuff.

01:11:18.200 --> 01:11:22.959
And with PMDA, we even suggested

01:11:22.959 --> 01:11:27.200
that we would submit RDS files instead of XPT files,

01:11:27.200 --> 01:11:29.839
just because we had these huge datasets

01:11:29.839 --> 01:11:34.359
that were more than 250 gigabytes in XPT,

01:11:34.359 --> 01:11:37.879
which I think any local laptop

01:11:37.879 --> 01:11:41.839
would be difficult to open those up.

01:11:43.319 --> 01:11:45.640
And they've been very open.

01:11:45.640 --> 01:11:48.600
And I would say from all the health authorities

01:11:48.600 --> 01:11:50.520
that we have talked with,

01:11:50.520 --> 01:11:54.160
none of them are questioning the use of R.

01:11:54.160 --> 01:11:57.640
They are still coming with the same scientific questions

01:11:57.640 --> 01:11:59.359
about the submission.

01:11:59.399 --> 01:12:02.720
Of course, here we got some technical questions

01:12:02.720 --> 01:12:04.520
about restoring the environment,

01:12:04.520 --> 01:12:08.640
but it was because they wanted to make it work.

01:12:09.879 --> 01:12:13.120
So only positive things, I would say.

01:12:15.839 --> 01:12:16.959
Well, fantastic.

01:12:16.959 --> 01:12:17.799
Thank you again.

01:12:17.799 --> 01:12:21.319
I think this has been one heck of a webinar

01:12:21.319 --> 01:12:23.479
and the community is gonna really enjoy

01:12:23.479 --> 01:12:24.839
watching this afterwards.

01:12:24.839 --> 01:12:28.600
I suspect we also can tackle some of these other questions

01:12:28.600 --> 01:12:29.600
maybe in a blog post.

01:12:29.600 --> 01:12:32.439
So thank you so much, Ari, Steph, and Anders.

01:12:32.439 --> 01:12:34.520
Truly wonderful to hear about your experience,

01:12:34.520 --> 01:12:35.720
the journey you went down,

01:12:35.720 --> 01:12:38.439
and the collaboration with the community

01:12:38.439 --> 01:12:40.439
and internally has been fantastic.

01:12:40.439 --> 01:12:44.200
So with that, we do thank you one last time

01:12:44.200 --> 01:12:45.359
and thank you to the community

01:12:45.359 --> 01:12:47.600
that's turned out for the webinar today.

01:12:47.600 --> 01:12:48.759
And stay tuned.

01:12:48.759 --> 01:12:51.600
We'll be posting this online here soon

01:12:51.600 --> 01:12:53.959
for those of you that may have missed some parts.

01:12:53.959 --> 01:12:56.560
And hopefully we see you at R and Pharma

01:12:56.560 --> 01:12:58.080
coming up in October.

01:12:58.120 --> 01:13:01.040
And with that, we'll bid everybody farewell

01:13:01.040 --> 01:13:02.520
and have a wonderful afternoon.

01:13:02.520 --> 01:13:03.560
Thank you, everybody.

